entry.title: ash: Fix public user sign-in crash
entry.content:
Public user sign-in sets wallpaper under `UserLoggedIn`. This triggers

`DeskController` to check `IsSessionRestoreInProgress`, which assumes

the user profile is loaded. It is not the case for the public user

sign-in. This CL fixes the crash by making `DeskController` check

`IsSessionRestoreInProgress` when it has a valid `current_account_id_`.

`current_account_id_` is only set when the corresponding user has

finished sign-in.

entry.title: [FilesBulkPinning] Make DrivePinningScreen more resilient to restarts
entry.content:
DriveFS is prone to restarting due to configuration changes during

startup. This means the single call to `CalculateRequiredSpace` can:



1. Not get called due to the `PinManager` not being available at that

time (DriveFS is restarting).

2. Can get invoked, but immediately stop as DriveFS restarts straight

after getting called.



To alleviate this, restart calculating space if DriveFS is restarted.

This also adds a test that ensures the screen is shown if DriveFS gets

restarted.

entry.title: Simplify the build for branded strings
entry.content:
Branded strings are defined in *chromium_strings.grd and

*google_chrome_strings.grd files. Both kind of files contain different

messages for the same ids. Those ids are compiled into generated header

files by their corresponding targets. Both the targets and the header

files are named differently, similarly to the grd files. This requires

that the correct target and header file is used depending on the build

but, in practice, most code sites just depend on both targets and

include both header files.



This CL merges those targets so that from now on only the chromium

version is used (e.g.

//chrome/app:chromium_strings and chrome/grit/chromium_strings.h,

//components/strings/component_chromium_strings and

components/strings/grit/components_chromium_strings.h, etc.). The

targets are parameterized by `branding_path_product` so that the correct

grd and pak filenames are used.



Future CLs will change the targets and generated files to be named

*branded_strings.

entry.title: Attempt to fix usage of MetricIntegrationtest::GetEntry.
entry.content:
GetEntry calls GetMergedEntriesByName, which constructs a map with freshly allocated instances of mojom::UkmEntry; these are then returned by GetEntry. Therefore, one must be careful with the lifetime of the returned object, or it will get destroyed by the time it's used. Saying GetEntry().get() is only OK if it's then used within that same expression. Therefore, to make this less error prone, I've put the invocations into extra lines, so that even when the fixed code is copied and altered it'll likely remain ok.

entry.title: Revert "LoAF: support approximate source locations for promise resolvers"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 07a41b1a0d49acd929ba716332c65ec7c8c55a2b.



Reason for revert: performance regression.

See https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1475117



Will try to refactor and run pinpoint on the CL with that test.



Original change's description:

> LoAF: support approximate source locations for promise resolvers

>

> Attribute the source location of a promise resolver that contributed

> to LoAF to the script that created it, e.g. the script that called

> fetch().

>

> Getting the exact source location of the promise resolver itself

> would require capturing a stack trace, which might be too much

> overhead, so this is the next best thing. We can revise in the future

> whether a shallow stack trace is something we're OK with in some

> circumstances.

>

> Note that it's impossible to get the location of the actual then(),

> as that's a microtask that's batched together with all the rest of

> the microtasks (e.g. other then()s of the same promise).

>

> The animation frame monitor maintains a weak map between the promise

> resolver and the source location of the event

> listener/script-block/callback that was responsible for creating it.

> This source location is then used when a promise is resolved and the

> resolution task is a long script that contributes to the LoAF.
